      Healdsburg’s Chevoo wins North Bay Maker Award
	  




















GARY QUACKENBUSH
FOR NORTH BAY BUSINESS JOURNAL | July 20, 2017, 6:19PM 

07/20/2017



Order Article Reprint









Chevoo
140 Grove Court, Healdsburg
707.931.4400
Employees: 13
Founded: 2015
www.chevoo.com












With less than a year at its new Healdsburg home at 140 Grove Court, Gerard and Susan Tuck’s Chevoo Inc. artisan goat cheese company is increasing production to over 200,000 units a month, while expanding distribution from only 40 stores in December 2015 to more than 1,000 today in the U.S. and overseas — a number expected to reach 1,500 by year end.The company uses modern equipment, technology and precision planning techniques to streamline production efforts and efficiency, while also preparing for future product lines and possible new USDA food regulations predicted next year.To achieve this, Chevoo has deployed a combination of web applications and cloud-based programs to allow for easy data entry and analysis, while also optimizing employee work flow regardless of their location and current assignments. Together these high-tech tools enable quick decision-making in a lean manufacturing setting and a paperless environment.“We’ve had to pinch ourselves a bit in response to the widespread demand for our product. Well before Chevoo’s second anniversary, market acceptance has exceeded our wildest dreams,” Gerard Tuck said. “We are increasingly hard pressed to find specialty retailers in NorCal that do not already carry our products, and are expanding nationally.”The quality of the Chevoo product line is only part of the story. Behind the scenes, the company’s state-of-the-art, all stainless steel food processing and manufacturing facility produces its current range of marinated goat cheeses, as well as a range of other specialty food products.“The Tuck’s dedication to quality, food and human safety exceeds that of any company I have worked for,” said Operations Manager Cheriene Griffith.Entering the Chevoo production area is similar to going into a biotech clean room. Sterile coveralls, hats, shoes and gloves must be worn as workers transition from the administrative to manufacturing sections of the 10,000-square-foot building.“I once had a boss that asked me ‘would you allow your dearest friends and family to eat food made in your facility?’ With this in mind, we wanted to ensure that our production process was world-class when it comes to food safety,” said Tuck.This due diligence paid off for Chevoo when it came to receiving the Food & Drug Administration’s coveted SQF (Safe Quality Food) level 3 “excellent” certification in March — the highest level attainable. Furthermore, in less than six months, the company achieved OSHA Golden Partner certification status; the TraceGains Con Audit Readiness Award as well as being licensed as a California Dairy Plant. Chevoo’s products are gluten free and ideal for vegetarian meals. In addition, the company has also obtained organic and kosher certifications.More shifts have been added in response to Chevoo’s rapid increase in production and sales, but there is still time in the schedule for some contract manufacturing. Today the company’s plant is being used to make products for two other specialty food brands in California, more than tripling overall production.At the same time, Chevoo is planning to introduce two new flavors in October, including Tupelo Honey & Lime, and Black Italian Truffle. These products will be in addition to its current line featuring Smoked Sea Salt & Rosemary, California Dill Pollen & Garlic, and Aleppo-Urfa Chili & Lemon varieties. A new Chevoo product line is scheduled to launch in January 2018, but the Tuck’s are keeping their plans close to the vest until the reveal.



Chevoo
140 Grove Court, Healdsburg
707.931.4400
Employees: 13
Founded: 2015
www.chevoo.com


















